context: The term <a0_0><b6_0>cardinal<b6_0/><a0_0/> at one time applied to any priest permanently assigned or incardinated to a church, or specifically to the senior priest of an important church, based on the <b7_0>Latin <a3_0>cardo<b7_0/><a3_0/> (hinge), meaning <b5_0>"principal" or "chief"<b5_0/>. The term was applied in this sense as early as the <a1_0>ninth century<a1_0/> to the priests of the <a2_0><b8_0>tituli<b8_0/><a2_0/> (parishes) of the diocese of Rome. <a4_0><b9_0>The Church of England<b9_0/><a4_0/> retains an instance of this origin of the title, which is held by the two senior members of the College of Minor Canons of St Paul's Cathedral.
